<br>
Cheap computer to play EQ perfectly.<br>
<br>
AMD XP 1800+ (1.53 Ghz) or Pentium 4 1800 Mhz<br>
512 MB PC2100 (266 Mhz) DDR RAM<br>
40 Gig Hard Drive<br>
Geforce 4 Ti or Radeon 8000 series or better<br>
<br>
Nice computer to play EQ and EQ2 perfectly.<br>
<br>
AMD XP 2500+ or Pentium 4 2600 Mhz or faster...<br>
512 - 1024 MB PC 2700 (333Mhz) or faster (depending on CPU FSB) RAM<br>
40 Gig or larger Hard Drive<br>
GeforceFX 5600 or Radeon 9600 series or better...<br>
<br>
Everything else is negligible to playing EQ really. If you are going to build, or know someone who's going to build you one, make sure you have it build by these few basic guidelines...<br>
<br>
1. CPU needs a Fan &amp; Heatsink that is designed for much faster than your CPU is. Never spend any less than $20 on a CPU cooler. You wont regret it.<br>
<br>
2. RAM speed should be identicle to your CPU FSB (Front Side Bus). The FSB is the base speed at which your CPU runs at. An AMD XP 1800 runs on a 266 Mhz FSB and an AMD XP 2500 runs at 333 Mhz FSB. RAM is measured in speed also. If you have a 266 Mhz FSB, then buy 2100 (266Mhz) RAM. If you have a 333Mhz FSB, then buy 2700 Mhz (333Mhz) RAM. Anything faster or slower is causing bottlenecks. CPU FSB and RAM speed should be syncronous. <br>
<br>
3. Make sure your computer case has plenty of fans. Heat build up in your computer can seriously hinder performance or even damage hardware. Make sure there are fans to blow out the heat. Also, make sure you have the fan on the front of your PC blowing in, and the back ones blowing out. This creates an air flow, venting heat out more efficiently.<br>
<br>
4. NEVER buy a budget video card. These cards are built and designed on old technology. Budget cards might play modern games fairly well, but next generation games (EQ2) will not, and you will be force to upgrade if you want to play them. Longivity is a nice luxury in owning a PC, so you dont want to use hardware that has a short term life.<br>
<br>
5. Buy a 400 Watt Power Supply or higher. As computer grow faster, they demand more power. Having an underpowered power supply can seriously damage your computer hardware. Also, having a high powered power supply will give you room to upgrade for the future.<br>
<br>
Just for a reference, all popular brand name computers suck. By popular name brand, I mean the basic Dell, HP, Compaq, Emachines, ect.... Alienware computers are nice, but they charge WAY too much, for a computer you could build for 1/3 the price. Gateway computer aren't horrible, but they cut corners as bad as the popular name brands as well, unless your willing to pay at least $1000 dollars or more. Most name brand computers are designed to breakaround the warranty expiration. They do this buy putting lackluster cooling on the power supply and CPU, thus causing them to slightly overheat, and wear out. This or the fans wear out after a year or so of use, then stop, and your CPU or Power supply fries, sometimes damaging other components in the process. This has been proven true time and time again, and I can give you email addresses to hundreds of customers of mine that will tell you the same thing. <br>
<br>
If you can find someone to build you a custom PC, and you trust this person not to rip you off, then I would suggest you get them to. Custom built PCs are more upgradable, better designed, and more compatable than 95% of name brand PCs. Sure, that budget Emachines computer seems like a better value, but after you are buying another computer after the warrenty runs out, your gonna be spending more money anyways. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <br><font color=#A62A2A>- </font><a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie>Firiona Vie</a><font color=#A62A2A> - </font><a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9>OT/OOC Forum</a> <font color=#A62A2A> - </font><br><br><br><br>Powered By <a href=http://www.ezboard.com/>ezboard®</a> Ver. 7.31e<br>Copyright ©1999-2004 ezboard, Inc.</center></body></html>  